<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://search.csmonitor.com/search_content/0813/p03s01-ussc.html" target="top">Christian Science Monitor article</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Currently, the United States is the only major industrialized country that doesn't provide some kind of universal coverage, even though it spends more than 14 percent of its GNP on healthcare. According to the World Health Organization, that's more than any other in the developed world and yet it remains the only one with tens of millions of uninsured.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Does society have a duty to assist those who cannot afford health care? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ryanallenvaz>RyanallenVaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 619<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 4:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> I would rather see my tax dollars go towards a universal health care system instead of welfare or social security.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=750075">Jhetlae</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1833<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 4:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> I can think of nothing I want less in this country than socialized medicine.  I think it would be a complete disaster.  I've studied the medical systems of several of the world's major industrialized democracies (England, Australia, and France) and they are vastly inferior to our system in so many ways.  There is care rationing, wait times, increased bureaucracy, reduced innovation, lower payment for medical professionals leading to less talented professionals, and loss of patient choice.<br>
<br>
Our system may have its flaws, but going to socialized medicine is throwing the baby out with the bathwater.  Let's keep what's good about our system and fix what's bad.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1835<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 4:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> By the way, society does assist those that cannot afford medical care.  We have medicare for the elderly and medicaid for those who are not elderly but too poor to afford medical insurance.  People who become permanently disabled qualify for medicare.<br>
<br>
People who make too much money to qualify for medicaid can pay for insurance if they choose to.  I know that Connecticut has subsidized insurance programs that these people can qualify for under the Health Reinsurance Act.  The quality of coverage is very good.<br>
<br>
There are more safety nets than people realize.  One problem is that people don't know how to navigate them.<br>
<br>
The biggest problem I see is children.  Say your parents are morons and decide you don't need medical insurance, and then you get sick.  It's not your fault you got sick, or that you don't have insurance, but you can suffer for it.  I think we need to address that situation.  However, non disabled adults of sound mind should have the right to decline medical coverage if they so choose.  It seems like a stupid risk to take and I have always been careful to maintain insurance, but I don't think I should have the right to make that choice for others.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=treeslover>Treeslover</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1758<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 5:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1>   You also get medical coverage if say.. you are about to die from an automobile accident or what not.  They don't ask you for your insurance unless it's a &quot;non-essential&quot; medical care.<br>
<br>
  I remember back like 8 years ago when I had gone like 2 weeks with a building strep throat, it got to the point where I couldn't breathe air without difficult and swallowing food was getting impossible.  I went into the Emergency room and was treated immediately (within 15 minutes) without them asking me to fill out forms or questionaires or what not.<br>
<br>
  I would like to see some sort of baseline national health care as that alone would do more to prevent the massive costs we incur as taxpayers because people just let themselves go until it's life threatening usually if they have no form of healthcare. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1838<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 5:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> If we decide to expand the scope of national healthcare, it would have to meet certain requirements for me to support it.<br>
<br>
1) It must increase the quality of health care or maintain it at the level it is at for everyone in the country.  If it will lower the quality of the majority and raise the quality of a small minority, as would socialized medicine, I obviously will not support it.<br>
<br>
2) Costs must be reasonable.<br>
<br>
3) It must be privatized to the maximum extent possible such that competition ensures quality and cost efficiency.<br>
<br>
Ayiar does have a very valid point that often postponement of care until it becomes emergent or avoidance of preventive care causes a long term increase in cost to the system as a whole.  This is a very real problem.  If we can improve the quality of medical care while at the same time reducing costs across the entire system, it would be foolish to do anything else.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=misscheivous>MissCheivous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 5:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> I know Md and Va offer free health care for children through the state if you qualify. The income limit is not too low either. People just need to do a little research through their Dept of Heath to see what is available. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.comcast.net/~dremarian/wsb/media/68398/site1039.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=440005" target="top"><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:maroon;font-family:georgia;font-size:x-small;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Graph's toys</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aurianne>Aurianne</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mana Whore</span><br>  Posts: 1683<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 6:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> There's something to be said for a guaranteed minimum level of support. Here in Ontario, we supposedly have socialized health care, which sometimes has waits, sometimes doesn't. For example... last Sunday, I broke my foot playing baseball. I wisely forgot running shoes, and played wearing sandals. Then to make matters worse, after hurting my foot, I took the sandals off, and played for 2 hours barefoot. Smooth.<br>
<br>
However, when I went for X-Rays on Wednesday at the pleading of my physiotherapist, I was in, and out with developped pictures in less time than it took for my ride to go to the bathroom. Last several times I went in for medical attention, there was zero wait. Even at the emergency room. (though to be fair, that was a life-threatening emergency, I had an allergic reaction to some mushrooms)<br>
<br>
Personally, I like socialized health care. I like not having to worry about a guaranteed minimum standard of living. I also like the idea of some services being opt-in and not covered by socialized health care. If I want homeopathic treatment, I pay for it. If I want physiotherapy or a chiropractor, I pay for it. I like it that way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1840<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 6:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> Emergent or urgent care rarely has a long wait associated with it in the United States or in modern industrialized societies with socialized medical systems.<br>
<br>
The problems with wait times are generally for non emergency conditions.  If you have a broken foot, they'll probably see you fairly quickly.  If you are having a heart attack, you're pretty much guaranteed immediate treatment.  How about if you need knee replacement for arthritis, an operation on a slip disc in your back, or anything else that, while medically important, is not going to kill you if it isn't dealt with immediately.  In the United States, the wait will be much less (and there are many studies that have shown this to be true).  Canada and Great Britain both have long wait times for operations like this.<br>
<br>
Additionally, I know that in Great Britain care is often rationed.  For example, the state will not pay for dialysis treatment of ESRD (End State Renal Disease) in people over a certain age (60 or 65 I believe).  In the United States, such care is covered at any age with just about any insurance program you might be a part of.  It scares me to  rely on a government that can decide I'm not worth spending money on.  Give me private care where if I don't like the coverage, I can leave and choose other coverage.<br>
<br>
