<br>
Man is a being of free will. Man can choose to think, drift, or evade -- but choose he must. His thoughts determine: his character, his values, his emotions, and his actions, and so his thoughts determine his destiny.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1842<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 10:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Socialized Medicine or Moral Obligation?</span><hr size=1> The problem is that companies would stop providing healthcare privately if the government covered it at all, so people would be forced off their excellent private health care to crappy public health care.  (Well, not everyone, I pay for mine entirely privately, but most americans do not.)<br>
<br>
It would adversely affect wages and drive down the quality of physicians and other health professionals.<br>
<br>
It would cost a shitload, so now people are paying for private AND public health care, it's just too expensive.  You would prevent people from being able to pay for private healthcare because they'd be forced to pay for a private system they didn't use at all.<br>
<br>
Governments simply cannot manage things efficiently.  They never do, because they create monopolies and there is no competition.  Without competition, you cannot have quality or price control.<br>
<br>
It would deny people the right to refuse health coverage, which I think should be a choice for all adults of sound mind.  If they would prefer to keep the cash and not carry any health coverage, I don't think that it's the government's business to decide it knows best.  I think people should make their own choices.<br>
<br>
Hospitals and doctors could be forced into taking payment from the centralized medical program or not be able to survive.<br>
<br>
If anything, I'd support a slight expansion of Medicaid upward in income levels to cover more of the people that cannot afford private coverage without making significant sacrifices.  I could also support legislation ensuring a minimum level of care for children, as they shouldn't be punished for having stupid/lazy/poor (not implying those 3 always go together) parents.  I would like for the current system to remain in place for the vast majority of people, and possibly add coverage for those individuals who cannot afford it.<br>
<br>
Basically, I want to improve or maintain everyone's coverage, socialized medicine will lower the quality of care for many while increasing it for a small minority.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eloihim>eloihim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 454<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/18/03 10:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> health care</span><hr size=1> maybe if the government had to pay the premiums the price gouging would stop. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=misscheivous>MissCheivous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/19/03 1:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: health care</span><hr size=1> The only problem I have with the current situation in the US is insurance companies mandating how long you should be in the hospital. I understand that they probably do this to keep doctors from creating extended stays just to get more cash, but I have seen instances personally where the person needed addtional days in the hospital and the insurance refused to pay for any more time. The doctor stongly urged the person to stay but they couldn't afford it. This is true of all insurance companies not just one.<br>
