<br>
Prices would go up in a single payer system because there would be no competition.<br>
<br>
Miss-<br>
I agree that there are real problems with insurance companies essentially breaking contract.  You pay them premiums, and it's then their job to pay for needed medical care for you, as determined by your doctor.  Sadly, that isn't what happens sometimes, and they decide it's their job to determine how long you should stay in a hospital or what meds you need etc.<br>
<br>
These issues are even worse in socialized medicine where some services are denied to you based on age or illness in order to save money.  Not all insurance plans in the US have these issues, the trick is getting on an indemnity plan rather than an HMO.  HMO's are really a problem, but they are dying out because people hate them so much (for the types of reasons you list above).  We want to keep our health care between us and our doctors without the insurance companies deciding what we need done.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=merraharvaz>MerraharVaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 314<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/19/03 7:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: health care</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>These issues are even worse in socialized medicine where some services are denied to you based on age or illness in order to save money.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What system you know denies services to &quot;save money&quot; ? That isn't a characteristic of socialized med care. Just because you might see it happen in some systems doesn't mean it is something that always happens in socialized systems.<br>
<br>
The problem is often the lack of availability of services (not to save money). In socialized medicine it means a choice would have to be made on who would get the most probability of full recovery (or factors like that) out of an organtransplant, in private systems it just means the person with the most money gets it.<br>
<br>
Medical care is something all humans should have a right to by birth. The thought that money buys better medical care is repulsive to me and that's the main reason I support socialized medical care. <p>---------------<br>
The dorf formerly known as Merrahar...</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1847<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/19/03 7:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: health care</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What system you know denies services to &quot;save money&quot; ? That isn't a characteristic of socialized med care. Just because you might see it happen in some systems doesn't mean it is something that always happens in socialized systems.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We studied this in a college course I took at Dartmouth called &quot;Health Care in American Society.&quot;   We specifically looked at the English system and the fact that people over age 60? could not receive treatment for ESRD due to the costs associated with it.  (It's extremely effective treatment, but also extremely expensive, and must be continued as long as the person lives.)  We also learned that such policies are common in socialized medical programs, although not universal.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The problem is often the lack of availability of services (not to save money). In socialized medicine it means a choice would have to be made on who would get the most probability of full recovery (or factors like that) out of an organtransplant, in private systems it just means the person with the most money gets it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's not true.  In private systems, anyone who had the forethought to purchase insurance gets it.  In the US, anyone poor enough also gets it for free as part of government programs like Medicaid.  Also, in the US, if you are elderly you get it as part of Medicare.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Medical care is something all humans should have a right to by birth.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not quite sure that's true, but it sounds good.  I would like to see everyone have access to medical care who wants it, but that is not something socialized medicine gives.  I also think people should have the right to decline medical coverage for themselves (but not for their minor children) to save money.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The thought that money buys better medical care is repulsive to me and that's the main reason I support socialized medical care.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It doesn't really.  Anyone who buys insurance gets roughly comparable medical care.  Which doctor you happen to choose is a much larger factor in the quality of care you receive.  I guess maybe it gets a bit better at the extreme high end, but even the lower end insurance plans in the US that poor people are part of provide medical care superior to that offered in any socialized medical program in the world.  The people who get fucked in the system are those that do not purchase any medical care at all but are high enough in income to afford it (i.e. not qualify for Medicaid).  The others that can get fucked in the US system, which is imo the biggest problem, are children whose parents are too stupid, lazy, greedy, or irresponsible to get their kids insurance.<br>
